title: docs(error/nobase): Added trailing slash for base path
body:
Trailing slash seems to be necessary, otherwise `$routeProvider` does not match routes correctly. Following is not matched:

URL: http://www.example.com/b/foo/1234
```html
<base href="/b/foo">
```

```javascript
$routeProvider.when('/:id', {
   templateUrl: '/view/path.html',
   controller: 'MyCtrl',
   reloadOnSearch: false
});
```

title: feat($http): add X-Forwarded-* headers to requests
body:
.... for compatibility with RESTful backends (i.e. Spring MVC + HATEOAS) that are not beeing reversed proxied, and don't know for sure wich protocol they are beeing used.

I found that this could be an usefull thing to be done automatically by Angular as some frameworks (like Spring HATEOAS) rely in this information to generate absolute URLs (cause they expect a reverse proxy to set this headers for them). In a cloud environment (i.e. PaaS), or local environment, this frameworks are not likely to be reverse proxied (although they could) so currently there is no way other than hacking the framework itself, or creating a custom request interceptor in angular to provide this two headers so everything works .... 

I don't see any drawbacks (other than the little bit increased request size) in having this set automatically by angularjs. 

Also I have to change the 'should allow replacement of the headers object' spec as AFAIK $http could add other headers after the interceptor (as the ones I added or others like XSRF).

Would be glad to hear any feedbacks about the changes I made :-).

milestone.title: Purgatory
milestone.description:
This milestone is for issues and PRs that weren't accepted yet and we are waiting for more info from the submitter.

For issues this typically means that we weren't able to reproduce the issue or we haven't decided yet if a feature request is a good idea at all.

For PRs this means that the PR still needs a lot of work and we might not even be interested in merging it because it looks like a non-core feature. We are still waiting for more discussion within the team or more info from the contributor before making the final decision.

title: docs(ngModelOptions): Config objects cannot be shared among ngModelOptions instances.
body: Just thought I'd add a note about this issue since it hit me during development and I cannot find any note about it in the documentation.  Looking at the source code, it seems that the changes to the object made in the block of https://github.com/angular/angular.js/blob/master/src/ng/directive/ngModel.js#L1223 are not idempotent, but I guess that's a design choice, not a bug?
